found my role changing from group to group.  I did whatever they needed: when they didn't have a healer, I healed; when they didn't have a nuker, I DD'd; when they didn't have a tank, I pulled &amp; meleed.  Although I LOVE this variety, I don't know what I am suppose to be when I grow up!  I chose a druid after watching my husband play EQ for a couple of weeks because I wanted to be able to give people the things they were asking for: SoWs, Heals, Buffs, Binds.  Being able to help people is still my favorite part of the game and being needed in a group is important to me, so whatever direction I take this druid in, I would like to continue to develop that aspect.  I feel that I do not always use the best spells in some situations. I am frequently the only druid in my group so I haven't had a chance to learn much from others. I'm hoping that being part of the guild will change all that.  Since I hit level 20 I've been using my new travel &amp; tracking abilities to try a little soloing and do some fun quests.  I've also finally earned a little plat beyond what I need for spells &amp; I'm slowly upgrading my armor &amp; enhancing my relatively low wisdom. I could really use some tips from older druids about the spells they find most useful in various situations along with some tips for grouping and soloing and general advice on where to take this girl.<br>-Aeyla <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#1478A2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub65.ezboard.com/utorgan1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Torgan1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/13/01 4:35:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub88.ezboard.com/fepicheroes73161frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Level 21 Druid</span><hr size=1> Torgan, Level 31 Druid here.<br><br>This is my first EQ character so my advice is based around what I found wrked for me, and is not neccessarily the best way to do things.<br><br>At 21 my first bit of advice would be to go the Lake of Ill Omen. The zone can be crowded but the xps are unbeatable.<br><br>As for role in group, I found that I usually ended up as healer. That basically means you end up doing nothing other than heal and med. The only exceptions are really dammage shield, root and snare. Dammge shield the main tank if there is one. If more than one or two characters are taking hits then it is less worth while. It is always worth spending a bit of mana snaring everything to stop it from running away and attracting adds. And it is always worth keeping root handy in case something starts beating on you so you can snare it and step back. If after a few fights you notice you consistently have plenty of spare mana then it may be worth throwing in the odd DOT if fights are lasting a minute or more, or DD if not.<br><br>As for soloing, at that level I tended to spend most of my time porcupining blues. Pull the MOB with snare, run away a bit, dammage shield yourself and DOT the MOB and then melee. It seems to be fairly effective and helps you keep your combat skills up. At later levels you will find yourself less and less effective at melee, so you may as well enjoy it while you have the chance.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#7c96b9><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub65.ezboard.com/uthumpslots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thumpslots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 181<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/13/01 12:28:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub88.ezboard.com/fepicheroes73161frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Level 21 Druid</span><hr size=1> The Role of a Druid huh?<br>Well this is my 3rd 50 plus druid.<br>Why cause I love em, I am Thumps and I can oh so relate to him.<br>You already have your role figured out and do not know it yet.<br>You are a jack of all trades.<br>You will fill in a group whatever it needs.<br>That means there are times when no group wants you, fine solo. You rock at it.<br>The things Druid does best in a group.<br>Snare, Damage Shields and DOTs, healing the primary healer.<br>Also soften up the mob with your DDs if mana allows.<br>You will find that as you grow you will tend to group with the same people a lot. They will grow used to you and allow you to do things that help the group.<br>You will be attractive to groups because you can get them where they need to be and keep them safe after they are there, knowing the evac is there.<br>A fun thing to do is to group with a Shammie, Ench, Necro and You.<br>You pull the mob, snare, root him.<br>Now the fun begins.<br>The chanter will lower his resists, you all slam your DOTs on him, and sit and watch him.<br>You will laugh at how fast the mob's HP bar falls.<br>He breaks root, stand and root again.<br>You can take out bright red mobs with ease and that is a fact.<br>I do not know how many times the wife and I (Necro and Druid) using this tactic have been told it ought to be illegal.<br>She and I would do HGs non-stop all day, the mob drops, I am at 60% she is at 50% I grab another and we do it again.<br><br>Another thing to consider is your specialty.<br>Think it over very carefully.<br>Most Druids solo and speicalize in Evocation, their DD spell.<br>Now that root works so well, I would say that your DOTs are your most important weapon for soloing.<br>If you are a grouping Druid, then maybe your heals then are your most important spell and that should be your specialty.<br>Your style must dictate that, no one elses.<br><br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#1478A2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub88.ezboard.com/uaeylagentlesoul.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aeyla Gentlesoul</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.iconbazaar.com/dots/animated/pg08/8anidot5b.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orc Pawn</span><br>  Posts: 115<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/5/01 7:39:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub88.ezboard.com/fepicheroes73161frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Level 21 Druid</span><hr size=1> Now level 29 Druid! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   And only 3 blues from 30 and the big Specialization decision.<br><br>I have found out during the last 8 levels that I do not care much for soloing.  I do not have fun if I don't have at least a partner and I prefer a group so I am leaning heavily towards specializing in Alteration for my healing, buffs, snares/roots, &amp; travel spells which are the things I most use in a group. Before I commit I wanted to check back with you guys and find out if there is something I have not considered.  Hurrk's &quot;Guild Leader for a Day&quot; thread where you get to try to assign the classes into permanent 6-person high-level groups was a bit of an eye-opener for me.  It would seem that my ability to nuke, Dot, or shield folks later in life will not be especially important and that my ability to serve as back-up healer and porter will be what is desired.  That makes me feel Alteration will be an acceptable choice.  I have a lot of levels between now and then, however, and I may never make it to 50 so I want to pick something that will serve me well now and in the future.<br>What do you think?<br><br>-Aeyla<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#7c96b9><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub88.ezboard.com/uterranya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Terranya</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http: